Return to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have put forward a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, the middle-class jobs are also dying," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and vice chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I proudly present the Employee Authorization Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal options for discrimination on the basis of the organization of trade unions as in other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-union-minded forces.
The addition of the national employment law to create a possibility for workers facing discrimination to organize a trade union representation in order to sue for justice in a civil court - and to receive damages or penalty payments - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors are suggesting to their bill is the connection back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks that unions have faced in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and comply with labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac encouraged Arthur and his staff to pass a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware of the fact that the workers and their unions took a role in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that "the rights of workers to unification and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupies Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would have to organize themselves, and should raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly testified: "The right to set up associations to secure and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to reduce this right are null and void; measures aimed at this are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, as adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the other authors inserted a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to establish a trade union - and that this union should then participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - must be protected.
After these rights came under fire in America, it is indeed very wise to revisit the American ideal, according to which the working population must have the right to unite and make themselves heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labor movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, work has miraculously created a market for industry, raising the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
The story remembers, and we should do that.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and redeemed the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily halts law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday provisionally halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana, which lawyers say would have presumably led to the closure of all five of the state's abortion clinics.
This measure, which was elevated to law by Bobby Jindal, governor of Louisiana, in June and on the 1. Sept. is to come into force, would force doctors who perform abortions to acquire a patient admissions right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius around their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that doctors can continue to perform legal abortions for the time being while requesting such a right.
"The plaintiffs may continue to work in accordance with the law while seeking to obtain these rights," federal judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within a month, a hearing will be scheduled for the judge to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying that so doctors would gain more time to gain hospital admission rights.
"Today's decision means that the women in Louisiana are escaping a devious law that wants to deprive them of their health and their rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chairwoman of the Center for Reproduction Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state's five clinics to halt the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the verdict also extended to the doctors from the two clinics, who had not joined the lawsuit and had also applied for admission rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures in Alabama and Mississippi to be unconstitutional.
Key points of a Texas law that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights from doctors require unnecessary restrictions.
Abortion opponents counter that the measures serve to protect women's health, though some also welcomed the impact of a closure of clinics.
Only a doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient credit rights, the Center for Reproduction Rights said.
If all the rest of the doctors in the state are forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the surgery for fear of his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the ruling, representatives of the state of Louisiana said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions, while their requests for patient admission rights would still be pending.
