If you would like to take photos or videos underwater, there is a selection of devices.
The cheapest option is a waterproof point-and-shoot, like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which are available for about $300.
I took these photos at a family party with multiple cameras, all of which are available at a cost of under $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Check your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the battery compartment and other compartments are tightly sealed.
Also, set your camera to the photos or videos you want to take.
Some cameras and camcorders feature scene and shooting modes that optimize exposure time for the dusky underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, check to what depth your equipment is functional.
Some cameras are only approved for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models in our shopping guide and the reviews.
Take multiple shots - because many won't work out.
Point-and-shoot cameras feature an LCD that allows you to compose images, action cams usually not.
Even if you have an LCD, it is difficult to look at this underwater, and the correct image setting is a matter of luck.
So make a lot of shots.
If your camera has a series mode that takes a series of shots with slightly altered exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the further you move away from the surface.
So if possible, stay close to the surface when you take shots in a pool, lake or sea.
This will also allow you to bring more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Go close to the objects.
