Liberia is hardest hit by the virus, here alone more than 600 people fell victim to the fever.
Recently, health authorities declared the disease had penetrated into every corner of the country.
The virus has also spread in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Nigeria.
In total, more than 1500 people have already died, with thousands more infected.
Foreign companies withdraw employees
Companies everywhere in the resource-rich countries are suspending their operations.
Foreign companies such as the steel group Arcelor Mittal are withdrawing their employees, several international airlines no longer fly to the affected regions.
The local traders and farmers are also reacting: only a few merchants are still leaving their hometowns to get supplies.
In some areas in Sierra Leone and Liberia, which are under quarantine, among other things, the cocoa and coffee beans in the fields, which are important for export, are rotting.
The farmers do not dare to leave their home for the harvest.
Food is becoming scarce
"People are going to travel less and less," says Phillipe De Vreyer, Parisian expert on West Africa's economy.
The man, for example, who usually goes to the market and sells his vegetables, prefers to stay at home.
The population is therefore feeling the consequences of the epidemic directly and urgently: food is becoming scarce.
In the markets, the stock of basic foodstuffs such as rice is dwindling.
At the same time, the region, which is heavily dependent on international companies, is at risk of damage to its image - with far-reaching consequences.
The biggest danger is that international companies basically avoid the area for a long time, says Philippe Hugon of the French think tank Iris.
The decisive factor is how far and how long the virus will spread.
“Investors may have the impression that it is dangerous to live in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Liberia and thus also to invest,” warns Hugon.
The disease is also weighing on states' strained state budgets
The disease also burdens the already stressed state budgets of the affected states.
The rating agency Moody's fears that their budgets will be heavily strained by the high spending on the health system and additionally by the deteriorating economy.
The African Development Bank already promised to help out the health systems of the affected countries with 60 million dollars (45 million euros).
The effects are also noticeable in Nigeria, where so far only a few Ebola cases have been diagnosed.
The oil-rich region in the southern Niger Delta has not yet been affected.
But elsewhere, many people are already staying at home for fear of contagion.
Reservations in hotels are also declining significantly.
