Norwegian Cruise close to a deal with Prestige Cruises of $3bn
Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings Ltd NCHL.O, the world's third-largest cruise operator, is conducting advanced negotiations to acquire competitor Prestige Cruises International Inc for about $3 billion, according to experts in the industry.
A deal would give Norwegian Cruise, a $6.8 billion market value company, access to Prestige Cruises' luxury cruise ships, as well as its wealthy clientele, while competing with larger rivals such as Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd (RCL.N) and Carnival Corp (CCL.N).
An agreement could be announced as early as this week, sources said Sunday, warning that the talks could also end inconclusively.
The owner of Prestige Cruises, the private equity firm Apollo Global Management LLC (APO.N) also owns a 20 percent stake in Norwegian Cruise.
The sources asked to remain anonymous because the negotiations were not public.
Representatives from Norwegian Cruise and Prestige Cruises did not respond to requests for comments, while a spokesperson for Apollo declined to comment.
The Miami-based company Norwegian Cruise operates 13 cruise ships on routes between North America, the Mediterranean, the Baltic Sea, Central America and the Caribbean.
His revenues stood at $2.57 billion in 2013, an increase of 13 percent compared to 2012.
Prestige Cruises, also based in Miami, operates under the brand names Oceania and Regent, which jointly operate eight cruise ships on routes to Scandinavia, Russia, the Mediterranean, North America, Asia, Africa and South America.
It reported revenues for 2013 of $1.2 billion, an increase of 6 percent year-on-year.
The cruise industry is at a total of about $29 billion and in the next few years it is expected to be in place due to the strengthening of the middle class in emerging markets such as China and India.
The companies are trying to position themselves as the best choice for these new customers at the cruise operators.
Prestige Cruises applied to the U.S. regulators for the IPO in January 2014.
Apollo is the majority shareholder in the company since a $850 million deal in 2007.
Norwegian Cruise was formed in its current form in 2000 through a merger with a cruise operator owned by Genting Bhd (GENT.KL), a recreational and casino mixed corporation under the control of Malaysian billionaire Lim Kok Thay.
Apollo invested $1 billion in Norwegian Cruise in 2008.
Norwegian Cruise went public in January 2013.
Genting held 28 percent of the shares at the end of June, according to regulatory authorities, Apollo 20 percent of the shares and the private equity firm TPG Capital LP held an 8 percent stake in the company.
Carnival, Royal Caribbean Cruises and Norwegian Cruise jointly have 82 percent of the passenger capacity on American cruise ships, according to the original application documents for Prestige Cruises' IPO.
